260
00:14:25,881 --> 00:14:27,284
The power's lost...

261
00:14:28,309 --> 00:14:30,929
so nothing but the sound of rain.

262
00:14:31,180 --> 00:14:38,084
Then out of the blackness, Paul Westerberg steps to center stage with an acoustic guitar

263
00:14:38,165 --> 00:14:40,178
and plays "Here comes a regular."

264
00:14:40,284 --> 00:14:46,770
30,000 people fall silent to hear that one acoustic guitar

265
00:14:46,911 --> 00:14:49,819
and the one voice that accompanied it.

266
00:14:53,020 --> 00:14:55,219
It was transcendent,

267
00:14:56,587 --> 00:15:02,239
standing there in the darkness, listening to that song with my best friends.

268
00:15:05,161 --> 00:15:08,456
I think that was the moment in my life when I felt most alive.

269
00:15:10,404 --> 00:15:11,631
That's amazing.

270
00:15:11,802 --> 00:15:14,939
I would kill to have seen Westerberg in his prime.

271
00:15:15,037 --> 00:15:18,191
Well, he finished in typical fashion.

272
00:15:18,403 --> 00:15:22,579
The song ended -- he smiled, threw up,

273
00:15:22,695 --> 00:15:24,567
and then fell off the stage.

274
00:15:30,956 --> 00:15:34,242
What? Yes, I had a second bowl. I was hungry.

275
00:15:34,405 --> 00:15:36,454
It's not that. I was just remembering.

276
00:15:36,582 --> 00:15:37,848
Remembering what?

277
00:15:38,003 --> 00:15:39,218
Your hair.

278
00:15:39,470 --> 00:15:41,838
You wore it that way the first day you tutored me.

279
00:15:42,200 --> 00:15:45,671
You remember how I wore my hair the first day I tutored you?

280
00:15:45,777 --> 00:15:46,975
Of course.

281
00:15:47,113 --> 00:15:48,672
What else do you remember?

282
00:15:49,335 --> 00:15:51,258
I remember the ugly-ass poncho that you wore.

283
00:15:51,361 --> 00:15:55,866
Oh, my God, yes, you've made your feelings for that particular item of clothing very clear.

284
00:15:56,365 --> 00:15:58,688
Come on. Tell me really.

285
00:16:00,111 --> 00:16:03,896
Well... let's see, these jeans?

286
00:16:04,251 --> 00:16:06,840
You wore them the day we fell asleep in the park together.

287
00:16:06,971 --> 00:16:08,671
And these shoes?

288
00:16:08,791 --> 00:16:12,295
You wore these the day we got stuck at the DMV for five hours

289
00:16:12,404 --> 00:16:16,337
while we waited for your new license with my last name on it.

290
00:16:17,398 --> 00:16:18,572
What about my shirt?

291
00:16:20,645 --> 00:16:23,902
You wore that shirt one morning when you sat in the living room

292
00:16:24,021 --> 00:16:26,499
and you were playing that Beatles song on your guitar.

293
00:16:26,901 --> 00:16:29,773
The sun just framed your face so perfectly.

294
00:16:31,180 --> 00:16:32,516
"Blackbird."

295
00:16:33,472 --> 00:16:35,735
That was the name of the Beatles song I played.

296
00:16:37,487 --> 00:16:39,401
I remember more than you think.

297
00:16:42,438 --> 00:16:45,155
I can't believe I didn't notice this.

298
00:16:45,997 --> 00:16:49,011
This is the first dollar I ever earned in this café.

299
00:16:49,503 --> 00:16:51,029
Now it's ruined.

300
00:16:51,655 --> 00:16:53,586
Well, it's just a dollar.

301
00:16:55,033 --> 00:16:57,085
Don't you remember who gave it to me?

302
00:16:57,205 --> 00:16:58,610
Of course I do.

303
00:17:00,983 --> 00:17:03,939
I bought the first cup of coffee the morning you opened.

304
00:17:04,309 --> 00:17:07,445
I had Lucas on one hip, a tray on the other.

305
00:17:07,595 --> 00:17:11,604
My parents thought I was crazy, as did the rest of the town.

306
00:17:12,588 --> 00:17:13,839
Except for you.

307
00:17:16,381 --> 00:17:18,456
I'll never forget what you said.

308
00:17:19,957 --> 00:17:22,595
"Anyone who thinks this is more than you can handle

309
00:17:22,699 --> 00:17:25,652
is less than the kind of person you need in your life."

310
00:17:26,016 --> 00:17:27,870
I can't believe you remembered that.

311
00:17:27,972 --> 00:17:31,715
Oh, please, I stayed up all the night before, trying to figure out what I was gonna say.

312
00:17:34,982 --> 00:17:37,313
How about a kiss instead of a coffee?

313
00:17:59,914 --> 00:18:04,674
Keith! Keith! Keith! Keith!

314
00:18:04,883 --> 00:18:05,913
Shh!

315
00:18:07,442 --> 00:18:10,259
It's just a storm, Danny. It'll pass over soon.

316
00:18:10,353 --> 00:18:11,793
I'm scared.

317
00:18:14,524 --> 00:18:16,427
Here. Hold on to this.

318
00:18:16,512 --> 00:18:21,038
This way I'll always be with you. It'll keep you safe. I promise.

319
00:18:22,081 --> 00:18:23,512
Now go to sleep.

320
00:18:41,503 --> 00:18:44,851
Brooke, I'm sorry I said that. You're not psychotic, a little disturbed, maybe.

321
00:18:44,937 --> 00:18:45,949
You think this is funny?

322
00:18:46,040 --> 00:18:49,083
No, what I think is I think you're trying to sabotage us.

323
00:18:49,164 --> 00:18:51,091
Find any reason you can, so you can end it,

324
00:18:51,176 --> 00:18:52,849
so that you don't have to worry about getting hurt again.

325
00:18:52,938 --> 00:18:57,567
But the same words, Lucas -- the exact same words?

326
00:18:58,903 --> 00:19:01,060
I never sent that letter to Peyton.

327
00:19:01,160 --> 00:19:05,281
And I never sent my letters to you, either, but they still meant something.

328
00:19:05,697 --> 00:19:08,846
Just tell me, why me this time? Why not Peyton?

329
00:19:08,940 --> 00:19:11,320
I can't say anything bad about Peyton.

330
00:19:11,437 --> 00:19:13,722
She's my friend. She's your best friend.

331
00:19:13,819 --> 00:19:15,970
That's okay. You can say bad things about her.

332
00:19:16,068 --> 00:19:17,396
Oh, Brooke.

333
00:19:20,325 --> 00:19:22,377
The truth is I care about Peyton.

334
00:19:22,472 --> 00:19:24,533
Then what is the difference?

335
00:19:24,641 --> 00:19:26,239
The difference?

336
00:19:26,367 --> 00:19:29,342
The difference is I love you, Brooke.

337
00:19:30,902 --> 00:19:32,879
I want to be with you, not Peyton.

338
00:19:32,986 --> 00:19:36,173
But why? I need to know why.

339
00:19:36,280 --> 00:19:40,177
Because you kink your eyebrow when you're trying to be cute.

340
00:19:40,288 --> 00:19:44,319
Because you quote Camus even though I've never actually seen you read.

341
00:19:44,479 --> 00:19:48,543
Because  you miss your parents, but you'll never admit that.

342
00:19:49,322 --> 00:19:54,933
And because I've given exactly two of these embarrassing speeches in my entire life

343
00:19:55,042 --> 00:19:57,155
and they've both been with you.

344
00:19:58,837 --> 00:20:01,766
And that's got to mean something, right?

345
00:20:05,599 --> 00:20:09,921
And because we're both gonna get pneumonia.

346
00:20:10,826 --> 00:20:13,558
But if you need to hear why I love you,

347
00:20:13,976 --> 00:20:15,579
I can go on all night.

348
00:20:16,315 --> 00:20:17,711
You did pretty good.

349
00:20:34,762 --> 00:20:37,803
Hey, Rachel, can I ask you a question?

350
00:20:39,300 --> 00:20:42,045
I get all that stuff about being confident,

351
00:20:42,160 --> 00:20:47,020
but I'm still trying to figure out why you invited me over here in the first place.

352
00:20:47,149 --> 00:20:48,778
I thought we were gonna watch a movie.

353
00:20:48,879 --> 00:20:52,237
Well, I know, but our friendship.

354
00:20:52,443 --> 00:20:53,625
Why me?

355
00:20:54,530 --> 00:20:55,779
Are you kidding me?

356
00:20:56,418 --> 00:21:00,091
You are more honest and comfortable about who you are

357
00:21:00,177 --> 00:21:01,888
than most of the other guys in school.

358
00:21:01,988 --> 00:21:03,315
Is it that?

359
00:21:04,336 --> 00:21:07,213
Or is it because you thought it would make Brooke jealous?

360
00:21:08,888 --> 00:21:12,884
No offense, Mouth, but I don't need you to make Brooke jealous.

361
00:21:12,990 --> 00:21:14,894
Great. I don't even get that.

362
00:21:15,853 --> 00:21:20,451
There was something kind of cool about feeling like the pawn between two hot girls.

363
00:21:21,639 --> 00:21:26,403
Look, let me help you, give you the benefit of my expertise,

364
00:21:26,514 --> 00:21:30,666
and teach you how to become one of the guys the elite girls drool over.

365
00:21:30,787 --> 00:21:32,344
By being mean to them.

366
00:21:32,458 --> 00:21:34,100
Sometimes.

367
00:21:34,659 --> 00:21:36,914
But I'm not that guy, Rachel,

368
00:21:37,025 --> 00:21:38,437
and I don't want to be.

369
00:21:38,552 --> 00:21:41,509
So maybe the elite girls just aren't for me.

370
00:21:41,628 --> 00:21:46,780
But one of these days, I'm gonna meet a girl who really loves me.

371
00:21:46,903 --> 00:21:50,290
Maybe she won't be what you'll call hot, but I'll think she's beautiful,

372
00:21:50,400 --> 00:21:52,187
and I'll tell her so.

373
00:21:52,326 --> 00:21:56,033
I won't be mean to her because I won't have to play games with her.

374
00:21:56,762 --> 00:22:01,828
I'll just be the guy that she can always count on and that'll be enough.

375
00:22:02,651 --> 00:22:05,775
And she'll be elite to me.

376
00:22:10,943 --> 00:22:12,175
Are you okay?

377
00:22:12,971 --> 00:22:14,105
Not really.

378
00:22:14,731 --> 00:22:17,800
What are we doing? You've been here three weeks, Ellie,

379
00:22:17,902 --> 00:22:23,827
and all we've talked about is music and the CD and business.

380
00:22:24,224 --> 00:22:26,816
But it's not just a business arrangement, is it?

381
00:22:28,160 --> 00:22:30,125
Of course not.

382
00:22:33,754 --> 00:22:37,331
I need you to talk to me about your cancer.

383
00:22:45,995 --> 00:22:46,953
It's okay.

384
00:22:47,061 --> 00:22:50,976
No. No, it's not okay.

385
00:22:51,083 --> 00:22:53,922
How can you just act like nothing's wrong?

386
00:22:55,105 --> 00:22:58,277
Aren't you afraid? Because I'm afraid for you.

387
00:23:02,604 --> 00:23:04,495
Don't be afraid, Peyton.

388
00:23:06,195 --> 00:23:08,399
Every song has a coda,

389
00:23:08,511 --> 00:23:10,527
a final movement.

390
00:23:10,647 --> 00:23:13,559
Whether it fades out or crashes away,

391
00:23:13,673 --> 00:23:15,798
every song ends.

392
00:23:15,920 --> 00:23:18,607
Is that any reason not to enjoy the music?

393
00:23:18,746 --> 00:23:21,860
It doesn't mean I can't want it to not end.

394
00:23:23,310 --> 00:23:24,506
Look at you.

395
00:23:26,176 --> 00:23:30,203
You've had more life-changing events in the first 17 years of your life

396
00:23:30,282 --> 00:23:32,140
than I'd wish on anyone.

397
00:23:32,862 --> 00:23:35,005
You got the surviving part down.

398
00:23:37,341 --> 00:23:39,902
I want you to focus more on the living.

399
00:23:42,848 --> 00:23:45,814
Sometimes surviving is about all the living I can handle.

400
00:23:45,918 --> 00:23:48,406
I don't buy that for one second.

401
00:23:48,821 --> 00:23:53,577
And if you keep this up, hiding in your art and your sadness,

402
00:23:53,700 --> 00:23:55,685
you're really gonna miss out.

403
00:23:55,939 --> 00:23:57,798
Because the truth is

404
00:23:58,320 --> 00:24:01,115
there is nothing to be afraid of.

405
00:24:01,757 --> 00:24:04,195
It's just life.

406
00:24:06,628 --> 00:24:07,605
Come on.

407
00:24:08,648 --> 00:24:09,867
Come on.

408
00:24:10,029 --> 00:24:11,497
Where are we going?

409
00:24:12,457 --> 00:24:14,662
We are going into life.

410
00:24:17,416 --> 00:24:22,744
I really like that you're telling me all these stories about how much you remember.

411
00:24:22,995 --> 00:24:26,136
It's kind of scary, though. Now I have to be, like, supercute 24-7

412
00:24:26,226 --> 00:24:28,966
if it's gonna be embedded in your memory for all of eternity.

413
00:24:29,070 --> 00:24:32,692
But I have to say I kind of feel like we're cheating.

414
00:24:32,768 --> 00:24:35,450
We're not even really talking about all the big issues.

415
00:24:35,545 --> 00:24:38,812
I was this close to getting away with it, wasn't I?

416
00:24:39,390 --> 00:24:40,677
I don't want to ruin our evening.

417
00:24:40,778 --> 00:24:44,622
I just don't want to miss an opportunity to actually work things out.

418
00:24:45,270 --> 00:24:48,861
How do you know a fun night together isn't exactly what we need to work things out?

419
00:24:48,956 --> 00:24:52,416
Or maybe a few fun nights all in a row. No trouble in between.

420
00:24:52,536 --> 00:24:55,817
- Yeah, um --
- I know. It's not your nature.

421
00:24:55,934 --> 00:25:00,843
It's not really, and I'm sorry. I can't help it. I have so many questions.

422
00:25:05,890 --> 00:25:08,662
Okay. Why did you call Chris?

423
00:25:08,755 --> 00:25:10,834
I told you. I asked Chris to come back

424
00:25:10,922 --> 00:25:13,177
and help you with your music because you love it.

425
00:25:13,273 --> 00:25:14,893
It's a huge part of who you are.

426
00:25:14,983 --> 00:25:17,399
I know, but, Nathan -- Chris?

427
00:25:17,494 --> 00:25:19,399
There were a million people you could've called.

428
00:25:19,508 --> 00:25:21,371
Why open that door again?

429
00:25:24,111 --> 00:25:29,512
Look, I called Chris because I screwed up and I wanted to try and fix it.

430
00:25:30,015 --> 00:25:33,102
Going to High Flyers made me realize how wrong I was

431
00:25:33,175 --> 00:25:34,831
to make you choose between me and the tour.

432
00:25:34,940 --> 00:25:37,554
I mean, what is this -- the 1950s?

433
00:25:37,658 --> 00:25:39,580
It didn't have to be either/or.

434
00:25:39,695 --> 00:25:41,359
But it was, wasn't it?

435
00:25:41,650 --> 00:25:44,250
Because I didn't ask you to come with me.

436
00:25:47,601 --> 00:25:48,596
Nathan...

437
00:25:50,535 --> 00:25:54,086
when I look back on the tour, I'm not proud of it

438
00:25:54,175 --> 00:25:56,464
'cause I know that you weren't proud of me.

439
00:25:58,643 --> 00:26:01,833
Is that what you think -- that I wasn't proud of you?

440
00:26:03,972 --> 00:26:06,195
Let me show you something. It's in my car.

441
00:26:06,535 --> 00:26:08,241
Nathan, it's crazy out there.

442
00:26:19,992 --> 00:26:22,374
Nathan, what are you doing?

443
00:26:38,590 --> 00:26:42,173
I was hurt, Haley, but I was still proud of you.

444
00:26:42,356 --> 00:26:43,620
Every day.

445
00:26:48,061 --> 00:26:49,510
Wait, wait. It's all getting ruined.

446
00:26:49,596 --> 00:26:52,700
No, you don't need all that stuff. You've got me.

447
00:27:27,477 --> 00:27:29,255
This is crazy!

448
00:27:29,406 --> 00:27:31,423
This is alive.

449
00:27:37,266 --> 00:27:39,348
You really surprised me, Mouth.

450
00:27:39,821 --> 00:27:42,195
That speech was pretty impressive.

451
00:27:42,325 --> 00:27:43,887
I was just being honest.

452
00:27:44,342 --> 00:27:46,642
The last part would've worked better as an exit line,

453
00:27:46,729 --> 00:27:49,670
but I watched Hurricane Coverage on CNN to know

454
00:27:49,764 --> 00:27:52,864
you're supposed to stay put until you get the all-clear.

455
00:27:53,752 --> 00:27:56,446
Then I guess we're stuck with each other,

456
00:27:56,557 --> 00:27:58,762
and I'm pretty much all talked out.

457
00:27:58,868 --> 00:28:00,511
You got anything else to say?

458
00:28:00,941 --> 00:28:02,264
Not really.

459
00:28:03,020 --> 00:28:06,057
Well, we could kiss.

460
00:28:09,290 --> 00:28:10,321
Stop.

461
00:28:10,821 --> 00:28:12,118
I'm serious.

462
00:28:12,433 --> 00:28:13,968
It would pass the time.

463
00:28:14,249 --> 00:28:15,490
What do you say?

464
00:28:17,644 --> 00:28:18,900
We could do that.

465
00:28:22,590 --> 00:28:24,664
But I'm not going to.

466
00:28:26,011 --> 00:28:28,612
Good. You're learning.

467
00:28:28,724 --> 00:28:29,728
Play hard to get.

468
00:28:29,822 --> 00:28:32,015
No, it's not that. It's just...

469
00:28:33,881 --> 00:28:35,968
it's easier in the dark.

470
00:28:36,099 --> 00:28:38,781
But pretty soon the lights are gonna come back on and

471
00:28:38,883 --> 00:28:42,293
we'll go back to being who we really are, right?

472
00:28:44,722 --> 00:28:49,233
I mean, kissing might be, I don't know, whatever to you,

473
00:28:49,476 --> 00:28:51,288
but to me, it'll mean something,

474
00:28:51,426 --> 00:28:54,100
and I'll wake up tomorrow wanting to do it again...

475
00:28:54,320 --> 00:28:58,148
and again and pretty much all the time.

476
00:28:58,957 --> 00:29:01,524
Somehow, I don't think you'll feel the same.

477
00:29:04,493 --> 00:29:06,384
On the day that changes,

478
00:29:07,242 --> 00:29:10,820
on the day you wake up and have to call me...

479
00:29:11,837 --> 00:29:13,412
then I'll kiss you.

480
00:29:18,314 --> 00:29:19,754
I guess that's my cue.

481
00:29:20,747 --> 00:29:21,705
Mouth, wait --

482
00:29:21,804 --> 00:29:24,198
It's cool. I'll see you later.

483
00:29:36,162 --> 00:29:41,106
Uh, you know, that lemon meringue was tomorrow's featured dessert.

484
00:29:41,488 --> 00:29:43,167
Well, not anymore.

485
00:29:52,842 --> 00:29:54,350
I love you, Keith.

486
00:30:12,824 --> 00:30:13,810
Gotcha.

487
00:30:20,120 --> 00:30:24,647
So, if you catch a cold, you can tell your father it's all on me.

488
00:30:24,772 --> 00:30:27,134
It'd be worth it. Tonight was amazing.

489
00:30:27,585 --> 00:30:28,680
Thank you.

490
00:30:35,499 --> 00:30:36,512
You okay?

491
00:30:36,653 --> 00:30:38,435
Yeah. Yeah.

492
00:30:39,499 --> 00:30:40,965
This is nice.

493
00:30:42,083 --> 00:30:45,049
Yeah. Yeah, it is.

494
00:30:45,647 --> 00:30:51,217
You know, um, I was thinking about the stuff you said about living life

495
00:30:51,317 --> 00:30:55,798
and jumping at opportunity, not being afraid.

496
00:30:57,357 --> 00:30:58,432
Yeah?

497
00:30:59,794 --> 00:31:08,329
And there was this guy. There is this guy I loved,

498
00:31:08,457 --> 00:31:13,869
and I let him go, and now I'm starting to think that was a big mistake.

499
00:31:15,058 --> 00:31:16,708
But it's too late.

500
00:31:17,132 --> 00:31:21,599
No, it's never too late, Peyton.

501
00:31:22,184 --> 00:31:25,202
That's one thing I learned from meeting you.

502
00:31:30,297 --> 00:31:33,641
I'm so sorry I missed those 17 years,

503
00:31:35,692 --> 00:31:39,220
but I wouldn't give back these three weeks for the world.

504
00:31:39,436 --> 00:31:41,074
Yeah, me, either.

505
00:31:41,917 --> 00:31:46,808
The Peyton that I've come to know deserves to get whatever she wants.

506
00:31:47,098 --> 00:31:50,661
She deserves to be happy as an artist,

507
00:31:50,983 --> 00:31:52,661
as a friend...

508
00:31:54,527 --> 00:31:55,914
as a daughter.

509
00:31:59,696 --> 00:32:01,258
As my daughter.

510
00:32:03,116 --> 00:32:04,583
I heard that.

511
00:32:14,455 --> 00:32:15,559
Stop it.

512
00:32:16,433 --> 00:32:17,473
What?

513
00:32:17,658 --> 00:32:20,434
Whatever you're worried about, just stop.

514
00:32:21,843 --> 00:32:25,361
How do you know I'm worried? You didn't even open your eyes.

515
00:32:25,476 --> 00:32:28,829
